Here's a JavaScript function that creates a transparent cover element at a specified z-index to prevent mouse events from reaching iframes on the page. It won't cause scroll bars to behave weirdly, and the `on` argument allows you to control whether the cover element is added or removed.
```javascript
function createCoverElement(zIndex, on) {
  if (on === false) {
    // Remove the cover element if it exists
    if (coverElement) {
      document.body.removeChild(coverElement);
      coverElement = null;
    }
    return;
  }

  // Create the cover element if it doesn't exist
  if (!coverElement) {
    coverElement = document.createElement('div');
    coverElement.id = 'coverElement';
    coverElement.style.position = 'fixed';
    coverElement.style.zIndex = zIndex;
    coverElement.style.top = '0';
    coverElement.style.left = '0';
    coverElement.style.width = '100%';
    coverElement.style.height = '100%';
    coverElement.style.background = 'rgba(255, 255, 255, 0)';
    coverElement.style.pointerEvents = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(coverElement);
  }
}

// Example usage:
// Add the cover element at z-index 30
createCoverElement(30, true);

// Remove the cover element
createCoverElement(30, false);
```
This function first checks if the `on` argument is false, and if so, it removes any existing cover element. If the `on` argument is true, it creates a new cover element with the specified z-index and adds it to the page. The cover element is transparent and doesn't cause scrollbars to behave weirdly because it is positioned fixed at the top left corner and covers the entire viewport with a transparent background.

